do_plot <- function(samples, size) {
  map_df(1:samples, function(x)
    tibble(X1 = runif(size, 0, 2),
           X2 = runif(size, 3, 4)) %>%
      map_df(~ mean(.x))) %>%
    # plot
    ggplot(aes(X1, X2)) +
    lims(x = c(0, 2), y = c(3, 4)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_point(aes(E[1], E[2]),
               color = "red",
               shape = 4,
               size = 2)
}
  

# 40 muestras de n = 5
do_plot(40,5)

# 40 muestras de tama√±o n = 20
do_plot(40,20)

# 40 muestras de tama√±o n = 50
do_plot(40,50)

$$ E(X_2 |x_1 ) = Œº_2 + œÉ_{21} œÉ^{-1}(x_1 ‚àí Œº_1) = Œº_2 + œÉ_1^{‚àí1} œÉ_2œÅ(x_1 ‚àí Œº_1 ) \

var(X_2 |x_1 ) = œÉ_{22} ‚àí œÉ_{21}œÉ_{11}^{-1}œÉ_{12} = œÉ_2^2 (1 ‚àí œÅ^2 ) $$ (a) Aplicar este m√©todo para generar valores al azar de un vector aleatorio con vector de medias \(Œº = (0, 5)\), desviaciones t√≠picas \((œÉ_1 , œÉ_2) = (2,3)\) y correlaci√≥n \(œÅ = 0.5\).

dif <- (as.vector(mi_mean) - c(5,4,3))
p <- dim(mat)[2]
n <- dim(mat)[1]


T_2 <- n * t(dif) %*% solve(cov(mat)) %*% dif

F_val <- (n-p)/(p*(n-1)) * T_2

p_val <- pf(F_val, p, n-p, lower.tail = F)


c('T^2' = T_2, F = F_val, p_val = p_val)
